# Go Dependabot / module hygiene

## What went wrong (WalkieTalkie, 2026-07)

GitHub Dependabot reported ~22 vulnerabilities on `main` (mostly critical/high `golang.org/x/crypto` and moderate `golang.org/x/net`).

**Cause:** `go.work` unified the *build* to patched versions from `core/`, but **`server/go.mod` still pinned** `golang.org/x/crypto v0.33.0` and `golang.org/x/net v0.35.0`. Dependabot scans **each `go.mod` / `go.sum` independently** — workspace resolution does not clear alerts.

**Fix applied:** bump Go to **1.26.5**, upgrade those pins (crypto **≥ 0.54**, net **≥ 0.57**), tidy both modules, `replace` local `core`, patch server to **1.1.1**. See commit `66855b5`.

## Rules (always)

1. After any Go dependency change, release prep, or Dependabot complaint: check **every** module with `GOWORK=off`, not only the workspace view.
2. Bump vulnerable `x/crypto` / `x/net` (and other flagged modules) in **each** `go.mod`, then `go mod tidy` + `go work sync`.
3. Keep the Go `toolchain` / `go` directive on the current patch of the active series (stdlib vulns need point releases).
4. Verify with `govulncheck ./...` on that toolchain; OSV/`GHSA` counts on the versions **written in go.mod** matter for Dependabot.
5. Unfixable noise: `GO-2026-5932` (`x/crypto/openpgp` unmaintained) — dismiss in GitHub if unused; do not block releases on it alone.
6. Patch-bump the affected app `VERSION` when shipping the security bump.

Never assume "builds fine under `go.work`" means Dependabot is clean.
